# tape-six-puppeteer — AI Agent Rules

## Project identity

tape-six-puppeteer is a Puppeteer-based browser test runner for tape-six. Runs each test file in its own browser context (page + iframe, isolated cookies/storage) in a headless engine — Chromium (default) or Firefox, selectable via `--browser`. Works with Node, Deno, and Bun. The npm package name is `tape-six-puppeteer` and the CLI command is `tape6-puppeteer`.

## Critical rules

- **ESM-only.** The project is `"type": "module"`. Use `import`/`export` syntax.
- **No transpilation.** Code runs directly in all target runtimes.
- **Minimal dependencies.** Only `puppeteer` and `tape-six`. Do not add others without explicit approval.
- **Puppeteer's bundled Chromium** is installed via `postinstall` (`puppeteer browsers install chrome`). Firefox is installed on demand (`npm run browser:all`).
- **Do not modify or delete test expectations** without understanding why they changed.
- **No narrating comments.** Comments are short _why_-markers only — a non-trivial decision or constraint, or an algorithm reference. Never restate _what_ the code does; JSDoc only when explicitly requested.

## Code style

- Prettier: 100 char width, single quotes, no bracket spacing, no trailing commas, arrow parens "avoid" (see `.prettierrc`).
- 2-space indentation.
- Imports at top of file, using `import` syntax. No dynamic imports unless necessary.

## Architecture quick reference

- `bin/tape6-puppeteer.js` is the CLI entry point. Handles `--help`, `--version`, and `--self` directly. Otherwise delegates to `bin/tape6-puppeteer-node.js`.
- `bin/tape6-puppeteer-node.js` uses `getOptions()` and `initReporter()` from `tape-six` for CLI parsing and reporter setup. Ensures `tape6-server` is running (with optional `--start-server`), fetches test files from the server (via `/--patterns` or `/--tests`) and importmap, runs tests via `TestWorker`.
- `src/TestWorker.js` extends `EventServer` from `tape-six`. Launches one headless browser of the selected engine; each test file runs in its own `BrowserContext` → `Page` (isolated cookies/storage) with `__tape6_reporter` and `__tape6_error` exposed as page functions and the test in an iframe inside that page.
- Browser selection: `--browser <chromium|firefox>` / `-b` (env `TAPE6_BROWSER`, default `chromium`; CLI > env > default). `#init()` dynamic-picks via `puppeteer.launch({browser})`, mapping `chromium`→`chrome`; Firefox runs over WebDriver BiDi; `--no-sandbox` is Chromium-only. `supportedBrowsers` (exported from `src/TestWorker.js`) is the source of truth the CLI validates against. A launch failure reports a failure so the run exits non-zero. WebKit is Playwright-only (use tape-six-playwright).
- For `.html` files: loaded as iframe `src` with query parameters.
- For `.js`/`.mjs` files: HTML document written into iframe with importmap and dynamic module script.
- Unsupported extensions (`.cjs`, `.ts`, `.cts`, `.mts`) are skipped with a warning.
- Worker control channel: `destroyTask(id, reason)` is the provider side of tape-six's control plane. `done` closes the task's context; `failOnce`/`timeout` cooperatively drain the test (post `tape6-terminate` into the iframe), then force-kill by closing the context after `graceTimeout` (`TAPE6_GRACE_TIMEOUT`, default 5000). Completion is driven by the page `close` event, not a reported event, so a force-killed page still completes `close(id)` exactly once.

## Verification commands

- `npm test` — run headless browser tests on Chromium (auto-starts server)
- `npm run test:firefox` — run on Firefox (requires `npm run browser:all`)
- `npm run test:bun` — run with Bun
- `npm run test:deno` — run with Deno
- `npm run lint` — Prettier format check
- `npm run js-check` — TypeScript type-lint of `.js` sources (`tsconfig.check.json`, no emit)

## File layout

- CLI: `bin/tape6-puppeteer.js`, `bin/tape6-puppeteer-node.js`
- Core: `src/TestWorker.js`
- Tests: `tests/test-*.js`, `tests/test-*.mjs`, `tests/test-*.html`
- Wiki docs: `wiki/` (git submodule)

## When reading the codebase

- Start with `AGENTS.md` for full project conventions and architecture.
- `src/TestWorker.js` is the core module — read it first.
- Wiki markdown files in `wiki/` contain detailed usage docs.
